      {
        "id": 35096,
        "name": "",
        "username": "5_c_d",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/5/35a633/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2019-06-20T01:22:12.031Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"johanw666\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/johanw666/48/9312_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> johanw666:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>very bad for other things like plausible deniability</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Yeah, signalapp is designed for this.  Not only can somebody with technological skills put together a false chat-transcript, so can anybody with rudimentary mspaint skills.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"IntentionalTypo\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/intentionaltypo/48/2100_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> IntentionalTypo:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>you get a separate phone number</li>\n<li>write some abusive and threatening messages</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>You can even set the addressbook-app to display that burner-num as ‚ÄúAlice‚Äù and then accuse Alice of having written the nastygrams.  And indeed, if you hire one of the ten millions programmers in the world, they can probably figure out how to modify the database directly for you, so it ‚Äúlooks like‚Äù the nastygram came from Alice‚Äôs actual signal-num.  That is all essential to plausible deniability:  Alice can truthfully say ‚Äúno I did not send anything like that‚Äù and yet Bob can at the same time be saying ‚Äúoh yes she did and here is the proof my device shows Alice sent nastygrams!‚Äù</p>\n<p>But it doesn‚Äôt matter what Bob‚Äôs device shows, as long as Alice‚Äôs device was secure, hers will not show that.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"yoasif\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/yoasif/48/3727_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> yoasif:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I know of no way to manipulate my backups to accomplish this</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Once we have cross-platform encrypted-backup-blobs, so a person can make a backup on signal4ios and restore it onto signal4desktop, and vice versa, or from/to signal4android and vice versa, that will open the doorway to making partial backup-blobs that cover</p>\n<ul>\n<li>just a selected subset of conversations</li>\n<li>during a selected timeframe / timeframes</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This has a lot of uses, the main ones being</p>\n<ul>\n<li>that you can link to a new device, and then restore your chat-history onto it retroactively (i.e. not immediately when you first link but at some later point</li>\n<li>that you can give the groupchat-history to a person you just recently added, without needing to do anything kludge-ish or manual-DIY-ish</li>\n<li>that you can make a partial backup-blob of your conversation with +2-222-222-2222 and restore it under your new&amp;distinct conversation with +3-333-333-3333 aka the person‚Äôs new signal-num</li>\n<li>that you can merge a portion of side-conversation that was 1-on-1, into a groupchat-history where that side-conversation is actually relevant</li>\n<li>various other handy tricks</li>\n</ul>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"yoasif\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/yoasif/48/3727_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> yoasif:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>there is no way to merge or migrate a dead conversation into a live one</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Until we get partial-backup-blobs, and the ability to restore them by dynamically merging them into a target-conversation (as opposed to only-full-backup and no-restore-except-at-re-registratoin which is what we have presently), there is only the painful workaround‚Ä¶</p>\n<ul>\n<li>if your signal-num is +1-111-111-1111, and your friend used to be +2-222-222-2222 but they are now +3-333-333-3333, you can</li>\n<li>open up the +2-222-222-2222 conversation,</li>\n<li>longpress on one of the chat-bubbles</li>\n<li>longpress on some of the other chat-bubbles (up to ~64KB of text)</li>\n<li>hit the forward-messages-arrow in the toolbar up top</li>\n<li>specify +3-333-333-3333 as the recipient.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This will kind of munge things together into a single huge chat-bubble.  And they won‚Äôt be in the correct ordering, either.  But it is fairly quick-n-dirty approach, that can be done fairly quickly if you really REALLY need it.  You can then archive the +2-222-222-2222 conversation, and if you get confused by the textblob in the +3-333-333-3333 which has copies of the prose, you can always open the old thing up again.</p>\n<p>The other workaround, if at least one of you has a linked signal4desktop device with the conversations in question, is to select all the chat-bubbles you wanted in the +3-333-333-3333 conversation with your mouse on the desktop, copy, open LibreOffice or compatible, and paste into there.  Then, once you‚Äôve collected all the chat-bubbles you wanted to copy, save the file as .DOC and forward it to your +3-333-333-3333 conversation.  This is not much use if you don‚Äôt have a word-viewer-app you trust on your device ‚Ä¶ by default on android those are opened in GoogleDocs, uploaded to the cloud without special prompting, so this is <em>not</em> a great workaround for sure!</p>",
