      {
        "id": 35116,
        "name": null,
        "username": "IntentionalTypo",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/intentionaltypo/{size}/2100_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-06-20T05:04:10.241Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"5_c_d\" data-post=\"6\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/5/35a633/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> 5_c_d:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>That is all essential to plausible deniability</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Plausible deniability is inherently at odds with Verify Safety Number and Bulletproof Crypto philosophy. If you have such security features implemented then, logically, it follows there is no plausible deniability, because authenticity and security of the comms is prime directive.</p>\n<p>We are stepping into the world where plausible deniability is <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0ybLCfVeFL4\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">unwanted</a> and authenticity and tamper-protection is the preferred mode of operation.</p>\n<p>Create such a video, hack their social media accounts, emails, etc. and frame someone of something. Before they can prove they did not do it, it‚Äôll be too late and very expensive.</p>\n<p><em>Chaotic technologies</em></p>",
