      {
        "id": 35382,
        "name": "",
        "username": "5_c_d",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/5/35a633/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2019-06-22T01:53:16.811Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"IntentionalTypo\" data-post=\"7\" data-topic=\"8139\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/intentionaltypo/48/2100_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> IntentionalTypo:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Plausible deniability is inherently at odds<br>\nwith Verify Safety Number and Bulletproof Crypto philosophy</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I think they are not contradictory.</p>\n<p>When she needs plausible deniability, Alice wants to be able to say that <strong>Bob</strong> is not necessarily telling the truth (e.g. Bob says Alice sent him a nekkid picture as a disappearing message but Alice says she did not ‚Ä¶ and her device shows no such activity either).  Sometimes, it is when somebody who <em>saw</em> Bob‚Äôs screen e.g. with a telephoto lens setup or something, and is claiming that Alice sent Bob something.  Alice can truthfully say ‚Äúthat could have been forged‚Äù.  Even if the verified checkmark is visible on Bob‚Äôs screen‚Ä¶ who can say Bob wasn‚Äôt running a modified client-app at the time?  That is plausible deniability, in a nutshell.</p>\n<p>Hardcore crypto, and safety-num verification, serve a distinct purpose:  of letting Alice know that (assuming her device is secure / proper / etc), from the UX and UI indicators, Bob‚Äôs <strong>device</strong> seems to be legit.  This is a subtle distinction:  the safety-num and the verified-checkmark are for +2-222-222-2222 aka Bob‚Äôs <em><strong>device</strong></em> not Bob himself.  Alice might <em>assume</em> that Bob is in control of his device, and that Bob has not given his unlocked handset to Eve, but Alice cannot <strong>know for sure</strong> those things are true.  All that Alice knows for sure is that if the safety-num hasn‚Äôt changed, and the verified checkmark is still being displayed, is that the person chatting with her is in possession of Bob‚Äôs unlocked device.  <em>Presumably</em> that is Bob‚Ä¶ but it might not be (per xkcd 538 and so on).</p>\n<p>Ideally it would be nice if there was a way to let Alice verify that Bob himself, was indeed on the other end‚Ä¶ and cryptocall with video <em>is</em> pretty close to that goal‚Ä¶ but not perfect, not definitive, as the recent video of fakeZuckerberg tends to prove.</p>",
